      The hedge fund business
   =20
 =20
I  often say that the key skill of a hedge fund manager is not=C2=A0picking=
 stocks that go up, but rather=C2=A0continuing to manage a hedge fund. If y=
ou pick stocks that go up, and a lot of people invest in your fund, and the=
n you pick stocks that go down, and then everyone takes their money out, yo=
u have done a bad job. If you pick stocks that go up, and a lot of people w=
ant to invest in your fund, and you say =E2=80=9Cwell fine you can invest b=
ut you need to sign a multi-year lockup with a very favorable fee structure=
 for me=E2=80=9D and go raise a permanent-capital vehicle on the basis of y=
our celebrity, and then you pick stocks that go down, and then everyone gru=
mbles about how they=E2=80=99d like to take their money out but can=E2=80=
=99t, you have done a good job. Obviously if you just pick stocks that go u=
p forever then you have done the best job =E2=80=94=C2=A0you are Renaissanc=
e Technologies? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that is hard. Not that it=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0easy, exactly, to keep your investors=E2=80=99 money even after picking =
stocks that go down. But it is a solvable problem, there are techniques for=
 it, it is more common than picking stocks that go up forever.Anyway here=
=E2=80=99s a story about how =E2=80=9CHedge Funds Are Hot Again.=E2=80=9D F=
or instance, =E2=80=9Cfamed investment firm Brevan Howard, which as recentl=
y as mid-2019 was struggling to stem an unprecedented client exodus, shut i=
ts flagship fund to investors earlier this year=E2=80=9D because investors =
were clamoring to give it more money than it could handle. =E2=80=9CHmm,=E2=
=80=9D you might think. If Brevan Howard (1) has more investor demand than =
it knows what to do with, and (2) just two years ago =E2=80=9Cwas strugglin=
g to stem an unprecedented client exodus,=E2=80=9D then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0perh=
aps it should reflect on the recent bad times, and use the current good tim=
es to=C2=A0stem the client exodus in advance?=C2=A0Like, when the investors=
 who took their money out two years ago are begging to put more money in no=
w, conceptually, what you want to do is say =E2=80=9Csure I=E2=80=99ll take=
 your money now but in exchange you have to promise not to take it out in t=
wo years when I start losing all your money again.=E2=80=9D And, again, the=
re really are techniques for that.Brevan Howard has found some?At Brevan Ho=
ward, the firm is determined to avoid a repeat of the boom-and-bust cycle. =
And a key part of that is talking more to investors, who in the old days di=
dn=E2=80=99t get much more than an occasional update and a phone call. Now,=
 even with Brevan Howard firmly in the throes of a turnaround, it=E2=80=99s=
 focused on holding onto client assets when markets inevitably turn again.=
=E2=80=9CThe issue is with the ability of the manager to stop investors fro=
m getting disillusioned and retain their confidence during inevitable perio=
ds of not-so-great performance,=E2=80=9D Landy said in a virtual interview =
from his home office. =E2=80=9CWhat we are doing very thoughtfully and deli=
berately is trying to be the best partners for our clients.=E2=80=9DFor him=
 and other senior money managers at the firm, that means grabbing a microph=
one: they all have to record podcasts outlining the thinking behind their i=
nvestments.Look if it were me I=E2=80=99d be demanding multi-year lockups b=
ut podcasting could probably work too.
