      Everything is securities fraud
   =20
 =20
Everything, I like to say, is securities fraud: If a public company does a =
bad thing, or a bad thing happens to it, and it becomes public and the stoc=
k goes down, investors will sue. =E2=80=9CYou didn=E2=80=99t tell us about =
the bad thing,=E2=80=9D they will say, =E2=80=9Cso we bought the stock thin=
king it was very valuable, but then when we learned of the bad thing the st=
ock went down and we lost money due to your deception.=E2=80=9DNow, technic=
ally, this is not always securities fraud. Companies don=E2=80=99t actually=
 have an obligation to disclose everything that happens as soon as it happe=
ns. If a moderately bad thing happens, and the company doesn=E2=80=99t say =
anything for a while, and then the news comes out, that is not technically=
=C2=A0securities fraud.But this is a small technicality that doesn=E2=80=99=
t matter much, because companies will generally have said something that th=
e bad thing renders untrue, or untrue-ish, or somewhat misleading. For inst=
ance, the company will say =E2=80=9Cwe have a code of ethics and tell our e=
xecutives to behave well.=E2=80=9D Then if the executives behave poorly, so=
meone will sue the company, saying =E2=80=9Cyou told us that you have a cod=
e of ethics, so we believed your executives behaved well, but you neglected=
 to tell us that they actually behave poorly.=E2=80=9D (This is the Goldman=
 Sachs Group Inc. case that went to the Supreme Court.)Or=C2=A0the company =
will have risk factors in its=C2=A0public filings, saying things like =E2=
=80=9Cif we get hacked that would be bad=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cif our chief =
executive officer is a sexual harasser that would be bad=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Cif we violate the law that would be bad=E2=80=9D or whatever. And then i=
f it turns out the company had=C2=A0been hacked, or the CEO is a harasser, =
or the company did violate the law, then investors could object: =E2=80=9CY=
ou lied to us! You used words like =E2=80=98if we get hacked,=E2=80=99 whic=
h implied that you had not been hacked, but in fact you had been hacked alr=
eady! Your use of the word =E2=80=98if=E2=80=99 was fraud.=E2=80=9DThat=E2=
=80=99s really the law I guess; here is a U.S. Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission enforcement action from last week:The Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion today announced that Pearson plc, a London-based public company that p=
rovides educational publishing and other services to schools and universiti=
es, agreed to pay $1 million to settle charges that it misled investors abo=
ut a 2018 cyber intrusion involving the theft of millions of student record=
s, including dates of births and email addresses, and had inadequate disclo=
sure controls and procedures.The SEC's order finds that Pearson made mislea=
ding statements and omissions about the 2018 data breach involving the thef=
t of student data and administrator log-in credentials of 13,000 school, di=
strict and university customer accounts. In its semi-annual report, filed i=
n July 2019, Pearson referred to a data privacy incident as a hypothetical =
risk, when, in fact, the 2018 cyber intrusion had already occurred. And in =
a July 2019 media statement, Pearson stated that the breach may include dat=
es of births and email addresses, when, in fact, it knew that such records =
were stolen, and that Pearson had "strict protections" in place, when, in f=
act, it failed to patch the critical vulnerability for six months after it =
was notified. The media statement also omitted that millions of rows of stu=
dent data and usernames and hashed passwords were stolen. The order also fi=
nds that Pearson's disclosure controls and procedures were not designed to =
ensure that those responsible for making disclosure determinations were inf=
ormed of certain information about the circumstances surrounding the breach=
.From the SEC=E2=80=99s order:On July 25, 2019, Pearson=E2=80=99s managemen=
t met to discuss the incident and again decided that it was not necessary t=
o issue a public statement regarding it. On July 26, 2019, Pearson furnishe=
d on Form 6-K its report of interim results for the six months from January=
 1, 2019 through to June 30, 2019. In the =E2=80=9CPrincipal risks and unce=
rtainties=E2=80=9D section of that report, Pearson stated that a =E2=80=9C[=
r]isk of a data privacy incident or other failure to comply with data priva=
cy regulations and standards and/or a weakness in information security, inc=
luding a failure to prevent=C2=A0or detect a malicious attack on our system=
s, could result in a major data privacy or confidentiality breach causing d=
amage to the customer experience and our reputational damage, a breach of r=
egulations and financial loss.=E2=80=9D This statement, which remained unch=
anged from prior Forms 6-K, implied that no =E2=80=9Cmajor data privacy or =
confidentiality breach=E2=80=9D had occurred when Pearson knew months earli=
er about the AIMSweb 1.0 breach. Pearson failed to consider how certain inf=
ormation about that breach should have informed this risk disclosure.Let=E2=
=80=99s assume=C2=A0that Pearson=E2=80=99s management was right and that =
=E2=80=9Cit was not necessary to issue a public statement regarding it.=E2=
=80=9D (The SEC seems skeptical, but does not quite come out and say that P=
earson was obligated to disclose it immediately.) It could have just burble=
d along keeping the breach quiet, until its next interim financial report w=
as due. Then, if it just left in the usual risk factor =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cif we get hacked it=E2=80=99d be bad=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0that wou=
ld become securities fraud; the hypothetical phrasing would imply that a ha=
ck had not happened, but in fact it had. I suppose Pearson could have just=
=C2=A0taken out=C2=A0the risk factor, but that seems like much worse disclo=
sure. (Certainly their risk of being hacked hadn=E2=80=99t gone down?) The =
advanced move would be to tinker with it a bit: =E2=80=9Cif we get hacked i=
t would be bad, and when we say that we don=E2=80=99t mean to imply that we=
 have not been hacked, perhaps we have been hacked, we=E2=80=99re not telli=
ng you.=E2=80=9D (For instance: =E2=80=9CRisk of a data privacy incident or=
 other failure to comply with data privacy regulations and standards and/or=
 a weakness in information security, including a failure to prevent or dete=
ct a malicious attack on our systems, which may have already happened, coul=
d result in a major data privacy or confidentiality breach causing damage t=
o the customer experience and our reputational damage, a breach of regulati=
ons and financial loss.=E2=80=9D) Even that might be too hypothetical for t=
he SEC though. Really the only move is to come clean. Your existing disclos=
ure boxes you in.
 =20
   =20
      Stablecoins
   =20
 =20
We  talked a couple of weeks ago about a core problem for stablecoin issuer=
s:=09(Many) people who buy stablecoins would like each stablecoin to be bac=
ked by exactly $1 in a bank account.[1]=09Banks often don=E2=80=99t want to=
 hold deposits from crypto companies (like stablecoin issuers), and these d=
ays they don=E2=80=99t want to hold deposits generally, meaning that they m=
ight decline your deposits or pay you negative interest.=09Also it is not r=
eally best practices to put all your cash in one bank account.=09So you buy=
 commercial paper and stuff, and your money is not all in a bank account.=
=09And then you go around saying =E2=80=9Cyour stablecoins are 100% backed =
by U.S. dollars in a bank account,=E2=80=9D because that=E2=80=99s what peo=
ple want to hear, but you=E2=80=99re lying.It=E2=80=99s not ideal. The cons=
ortium behind USDC, a $27 billion stablecoin, did this, and regretted it, a=
nd  has now =E2=80=9Csaid all the reserves of the second-largest cryptocurr=
ency stable coin will shift into cash and short-term U.S. Treasuries, forgo=
ing riskier investments.=E2=80=9D Fine. I=E2=80=99m not sure that=E2=80=99s=
 a good investment policy, but I guess it=E2=80=99s a good public-relations=
 policy, so fine.[2]=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know what =E2=80=9Ccash=E2=80=9D =
means in the USDC announcement. They=E2=80=99ll hold =E2=80=9Ccash and shor=
t duration US Treasuries.=E2=80=9D Presumably that does not mean =E2=80=9Ca=
 drawer full of $100 bills.=E2=80=9D Presumably it means bank accounts, per=
haps other things.You know what would be ideal? A stablecoin that was a pur=
e wrapper for a digital dollar. Right now you can=E2=80=99t get a =E2=80=9C=
digital dollar,=E2=80=9D in the sense of =E2=80=9Ca thing that is worth a d=
ollar in any imaginable state of the world,=E2=80=9D though you can come ve=
ry close. (An FDIC insured bank account is pretty much a digital dollar; yo=
u=E2=80=99d have to work pretty hard to come up with a scenario in which yo=
u lose access to=C2=A0that dollar even briefly. But FDIC insurance limits a=
re considerably lower than $27=C2=A0billion.)But=C2=A0some=C2=A0people can =
get pure uncut digital dollars. Those people are banks. A bank can hold its=
 money in the form of reserves at the Federal Reserve, and those reserves a=
re dollars in every state of the world: The Federal Reserve makes the dolla=
rs, and the dollars that it makes=C2=A0are reserves. The Fed will even pay =
the bank interest on those reserves; right now that interest is 0.15% per y=
ear, a small but positive number.A stablecoin issuer that held 100% of its =
assets in reserves at the Fed would be the purest form of stablecoin: just =
a blockchain wrapper for a digital dollar, a =E2=80=9Cblockchain depositary=
 receipt=E2=80=9D on dollars issued by the Fed. Nobody would worry about it=
s assets, because its assets would all be held at the Fed. (And it would ev=
en earn a little interest, which presumably it would not pay to customers b=
ut would keep for itself?)=C2=A0There are two problems with this. One is th=
at if you=E2=80=99re going to do that sort of stablecoin, you need to get a=
 banking license, which a lot of stablecoin issuers seem to find difficult =
or undesirable. The other is that the Fed doesn=E2=80=99t really like this =
sort of =E2=80=9Cnarrow banking=E2=80=9D; when a bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0called=
 TNB USA Inc., for =E2=80=9CThe Narrow Bank=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0tried t=
o open a Fed account to just hold all of its customers=E2=80=99 deposits in=
 the form of Fed reserves, the Fed  fought it and  proposed rules to preven=
t it.=C2=A0Still, maybe, who knows. Earlier this month, Felix Salmon at Axi=
os wrote:Crypto giant Circle has announced its intention to become a bank, =
fully regulated by the Federal Reserve, the Office of the Comptroller of th=
e Currency and the FDIC.Why it matters: We're still a very long way from th=
is happening. But if it does, Circle's USDC stablecoin could become a de fa=
cto central bank digital currency.How it works: Circle's dream is to become=
 a narrow bank =E2=80=94 one that eschews fractional-reserve banking entire=
ly, and instead places all deposits on reserve at the central bank. ...The =
big picture: If the dream were to become reality, then Circle would effecti=
vely be issuing a cryptocurrency backed by the Fed itself =E2=80=94 for all=
 intents and purposes, a central bank digital currency, or CBDC.The Fed doe=
s  not seem particularly fond of the idea of a CBDC either. One very genera=
l way to put it is that the Fed=C2=A0likes banks. Not so much in like a cor=
rupt regulatory-capture sense, but in the sense that, you know, banks lend =
people money and keep the economy going and so forth. The Fed is full of ma=
croeconomists and bank regulators who think that credit and fractional-rese=
rve banking work pretty well and are kind of important to the functioning o=
f the economy, and would be sad if everyone stopped putting their money in =
banks (real banks, that do lending and stuff) and started putting their mon=
ey at the Fed (or in narrow banks that park their money at the Fed) instead=
. Whether or not the narrow banks are also cryptocurrencies.On the other ha=
nd if you are a stablecoin it is a very appealing pitch! =E2=80=9C100% of o=
ur stablecoins are backed by dollars in a bank account=E2=80=9D is fine, bu=
t not perfectly risk-free; =E2=80=9C100% of our stablecoins are backed by d=
ollars at the Federal Reserve=E2=80=9D really is better.
 =20
   =20
      Broadridge
   =20
 =20
Back when financial firms were breathlessly announcing new blockchain proje=
cts every week, I made fun of them a bit. =E2=80=9CBlockchain blockchain bl=
ockchain,=E2=80=9D I called it. Here is the sort of thing I used to write:Y=
ou can bring senior executives into a room and tell them that you=E2=80=99r=
e upgrading the infrastructure that you use to reconcile trade settlement d=
ata with counterparties, and their eyes will glaze over and they will start=
 nodding off, and you can shout =E2=80=9Cblockchain! blockchain! blockchain=
 blockchain blockchain!=E2=80=9D and they will perk up and hand you a stack=
 of money. The blockchain is exciting in ways that improving database archi=
tecture is not.And I think that was true; the brief period of blockchain-bl=
ockchain-blockchain mania in like 2017 and 2018 was a rare opportunity to g=
et a lot of senior attention and money lavished on database upgrades in fin=
ancial services.Still it is worth saying that database upgrades in financia=
l services can be worth doing! Here=E2=80=99s an amazing story about Broadr=
idge Financial Solutions Inc.:Broadridge operates financial plumbing that m=
ost investors never think about. US funds and public companies are required=
 to share important documents with their investors. But because most invest=
ors hold stakes through brokers, their identities are often unknown to fund=
 managers and companies.Instead, brokers distribute the investor communicat=
ions =E2=80=94 usually by using a third-party vendor such as Broadridge =E2=
=80=94 and charge fees back to the fund or company.=C2=A0In the business of=
 investor communications, =E2=80=9CBroadridge is the leading player, by a w=
ide margin=E2=80=9D, said Rajiv Bhatia, analyst at Morningstar. =E2=80=9CTh=
e majority of shares are held in brokerage accounts, and Broadridge has eve=
ry broker except [retail broker] Robinhood. That=E2=80=99s essentially the =
entire market.=E2=80=9DThe New York Stock Exchange regulates fees for inves=
tor communications, setting a cap of 25 cents a report. Broadridge charges =
the full 25 cents for an email, according to analysts. It costs more than f=
or paper mailings because of a 10 cent fee that Broadridge charges to revie=
w whether shareholders prefer email over paper, according to the company.Th=
e fees vastly exceed the cost, according to the Investment Company Institut=
e, a trade group for the fund industry in Washington. For investor accounts=
 not held through a broker, a typical fund paid 5 cents to send a sharehold=
er report by either email or paper mail exclusive of postage, ICI said. ...=
Broadridge maintained that its fees represented a significant savings for f=
unds compared to what it costs to communicate with investors who own shares=
 directly rather than through a broker.=C2=A0The letter also noted that Bro=
adridge charged funds $45m for the year ending April 2018 to maintain a dat=
abase of whether investors chose to receive emails or paper mail from their=
 investments.I will not say that I have any special expertise here but, I m=
ean, I am a guy who sends out emails for a living, and I am pretty sure it =
does not cost 25 cents per subscriber per day to send out Money Stuff ? Als=
o I do not think it costs $45 million a year to maintain the subscriber lis=
t? These numbers seem high! If brokerages could somehow keep a list of all =
their customers with their email addresses, and could perhaps have a little=
 check mark next to each name saying =E2=80=9Cemail?,=E2=80=9D and could ke=
ep the costs of that list to the low eight figures, that would be a substan=
tial cost savings? It is possible that financial-industry executives should=
 be paying more attention to their databases.
 =20
   =20
      Pay
   =20
 =20
Here's a  Bloomberg Businessweek story from last week about how junior bank=
ers are getting paid more:In the span of a few months, the sticker price fo=
r a freshly minted college graduate in top-level banking has quickly shot u=
p, reaching and then surpassing $100,000 =E2=80=94=C2=A0a guaranteed salary=
 to be padded later with a chunky bonus. =E2=80=A6Out in the real world, a =
six-figure entry-level salary is another example of extreme inequality and =
the way finance has come to dominate the economy. The raises put junior ban=
kers on track to earn almost five times=E2=80=94or more=E2=80=94the median =
wage of young college graduates. By inflating paychecks right out of the ga=
te, banks are likely exacerbating the pay gap with other industries for yea=
rs to come.I dunno, I am not convinced that these raises are a sign of, lik=
e, the financial industry=E2=80=99s confidence and dominance? The round of =
simultaneous raises to respond to analyst grumbling suggests that banks are=
 keenly aware that there are other options, that the attractiveness of bank=
ing has decreased relative to tech or fintech or whatever.=C2=A0Also it rem=
ains funny that the analysts grumbled about=C2=A0the workload, and the bank=
s heard their concerns and considered them and responded with higher salari=
es:Adam Cotterill, who worked in the junior ranks of Goldman until last yea=
r, says it isn=E2=80=99t surprising that the solution banks have landed on =
is not so much to improve the job but to pay more. =E2=80=9CTrying to make =
changes to the life of junior bankers has proven to be really challenging,=
=E2=80=9D he says. To work through the crazy hours, Cotterill recalls putti=
ng on headphones blasting faux rain noise and taking power naps in bathroom=
 stalls. =E2=80=9CThere are a lot of negative repercussions,=E2=80=9D he sa=
ys. He left Goldman for another finance job, quit because of the strains, a=
nd is now a blogger.=C2=A0I know the feeling. Anyway this reminds me of a g=
reat anecdote in Gregory Zuckerman=E2=80=99s book about Jim Simons and Rena=
issance Technologies, =E2=80=9CThe Man Who Solved the Market.=E2=80=9D The =
story is about Renaissance executive (now chief executive officer) Peter Br=
own:Once, as he worked on a complicated project late in the evening, full o=
f manic energy despite the hour, Brown picked up the phone to call a junior=
 associate at home with a pressing question. A colleague stopped Brown befo=
re he could dial.=E2=80=9CPeter, you can=E2=80=99t call him,=E2=80=9D he sa=
id. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s=C2=A0two a.m.=E2=80=9DBrown looked confused, forc=
ing the colleague to explain himself.=E2=80=9CHe doesn=E2=80=99t get paid e=
nough to answer questions at two a.m.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CFine, let=E2=80=99s =
give him a raise, then,=E2=80=9D Brown replied. =E2=80=9CBut we=C2=A0have=
=C2=A0to call him!=E2=80=9DFor a lucrative enough business, the answer to =
=E2=80=9Cthey don=E2=80=99t get paid enough to work this hard=E2=80=9D is a=
lways going to be =E2=80=9Cwell let's pay them more.=E2=80=9D
 =20
   =20
      Benefits
   =20
 =20
At Quartz, Mary Childs and Karishma Vanjani have a rundown of =E2=80=9CThe =
best employee benefits at the top US financial firms,=E2=80=9D and point ou=
t how weirdly difficult it is to get the information:When you=E2=80=99re lo=
oking for a job, it=E2=80=99s difficult to find out what companies offer un=
til you=E2=80=99re far along in the hiring process. And if you already have=
 a job, there=E2=80=99s no easy way to learn what other companies in your i=
ndustry offer, to bolster your case if you want to ask your company for mor=
e. To attract top talent, companies should advertise their benefits=E2=80=
=94especially when they are great=E2=80=94but many of them don=E2=80=99t.We=
 canvassed 101 of the biggest and most influential companies in financial s=
ervices, one of the highest-paying industries in the US, to find out what b=
enefits they offer to employees. 32 asset managers, banks, industry groups,=
 and accounting firms shared this information.The basic form of the problem=
 here is that companies want to offer good pay and benefits to attract tale=
nted employees, but if they offer the best benefits they worry about the ri=
sk of adverse selection. If you offer unlimited vacation, are you going to =
attract mainly workers who want to take a lot of vacations? For a while Gol=
dman Sachs Group Inc. resisted the trend of raising junior investment banki=
ng salaries because it=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t want to attract workers who were=
 mainly in it for the money, which was a truly weird thing for Goldman Sach=
s to think but they did think (well, say) it. So you want to tell talented =
employees =E2=80=9Ccome here, we will treat you well,=E2=80=9D but you want=
 to avoid hiring employees who actually demand to be treated well. A compro=
mise is to say =E2=80=9Cwe offer competitive pay and benefits,=E2=80=9D or =
whatever, but make it hard to find out what they are.
