   =20
      The Poly Network hacker seems fun
   =20
 =20
A few weeks ago a hacker stole about $600 million of cryptocurrency from a =
decentralized finance protocol called Poly Network. Then Poly asked the hac=
ker to give the money back, and the hacker was like, sure, fine, I=E2=80=99=
ll give the money back. The money started coming back to a Poly wallet. =E2=
=80=9CCrypto Hackers Are Nice Now,=E2=80=9D  was my headline. =E2=80=9CTher=
e is some chance this will turn out to be a hilariously heartwarming story,=
=E2=80=9D I wrote.This weekend Kevin Dugan checked in on how that=E2=80=99s=
 going:Since then, the hacker parked the equivalent of $240 million in a cr=
yptowallet that=E2=80=99s purportedly shared with the Poly Network =E2=80=
=94 and then refused to give it the access keys for a week. Mr. White Hat t=
hen raised the bar for when he will return the funds, making himself the so=
le decider of when people will be able to get their own money back. On Wedn=
esday, another $100 million or so was returned =E2=80=94 the timing, and th=
e trigger for the rest of the money, remains unknown. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CThe=
 Poly Network team is still negotiating with the hacker. And the primary go=
al is to get one key back from the hacker,=E2=80=9D said Xuxian Jiang, the =
CEO of blockchain security firm Peckshield, which is working with Poly Netw=
ork. =E2=80=9CAt this stage, we really don=E2=80=99t want to make the hacke=
r angry to do something to jeopardize the funds.=E2=80=9DAh. (=E2=80=9CMr. =
White Hat=E2=80=9D is the nickname that Poly Network gave the hacker.) Well=
, maybe not heartwarming, but certainly still hilarious:In his missives, he=
 waxes philosophical about the nature of life, dropping references to Marti=
n Heidegger. =E2=80=9CI have been exploring the meaning of life for a while=
. I hope my life can be composed of unique adventures, so I like [to] learn=
 & hack everything in order to fight against the fate. Sein zum tode,=E2=80=
=9D he said, using a Heideggerian term for a state of being that=E2=80=99s =
oriented toward one=E2=80=99s own death.Despite the nomme de paix, this hac=
ker is ambivalent about the idea that what he=E2=80=99s doing fits into any=
 neat ethical category. In his communications, encrypted in publicly viewab=
le ethereum transactions, he refers to the heist he orchestrated as a =E2=
=80=9Cgame=E2=80=9D nine times =E2=80=94 one where the losers get what they=
 deserve.=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s hard to prove that your loss is my fault, es=
pecially when you are already gambling beyond your capability,=E2=80=9D he =
wrote in an all-caps message. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CIf you are still confused, =
ask some richer friends, what is money for?=E2=80=9D he wrote.=C2=A0Sure re=
turning the money=C2=A0seems=C2=A0kind, but=C2=A0is=C2=A0it kind? What sort=
 of lesson will the Poly users learn if the hacker steals their money and t=
hen gives it right back to them? He is not here to just do some hacking, ha=
ve a laugh, and give the money back; he is here to teach the Poly users som=
e hard but necessary lessons about money, about losses, about themselves, a=
bout the nature of being and time and this harsh universe. =E2=80=9CSein zu=
m Tode,=E2=80=9D he tells them, in all-caps messages embedded in Ethereum b=
lockchain transactions. Modern philosophy is great.
