<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The hedge fund business</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/24841104.252088/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDctMDUvaXQtcy1iZXR0ZXItdG8tYmUtcmljaC10aGFuLXJpZ=
2h0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB46489506" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: sol=
id; background-color: #ccc;"> often say</a> that the key skill of a hedge f=
und manager is not=C2=A0<em>picking stocks that go up</em>, but rather=C2=
=A0<em>continuing to manage a hedge fund</em>. If you pick stocks that go u=
p, and a lot of people invest in your fund, and then you pick stocks that g=
o down, and then everyone takes their money out, you have done a bad job. I=
f you pick stocks that go up, and a lot of people want to invest in your fu=
nd, and you say =E2=80=9Cwell fine you can invest but you need to sign a mu=
lti-year lockup with a very favorable fee structure for me=E2=80=9D and go =
raise a permanent-capital vehicle on the basis of your celebrity, and then =
you pick stocks that go down, and then everyone grumbles about how they=E2=
=80=99d like to take their money out but can=E2=80=99t, you have done a goo=
d job. Obviously if you just pick stocks that go up forever then you have d=
one the best job =E2=80=94=C2=A0you are Renaissance Technologies? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but that is hard. Not that it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>easy</em>, exactly, =
to keep your investors=E2=80=99 money even after picking stocks that go dow=
n. But it is a solvable problem, there are techniques for it, it is more co=
mmon than picking stocks that go up forever.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Anyway here=E2=80=99s a story about how =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24841104.252088/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMjQvZmlmdGhkZWx0YS1icmV2YW4taG93YXJkL=
WRlbWFuZC1zaG93cy1oZWRnZS1mdW5kcy1hcmUtaG90LWFnYWlu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB97d25f8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">Hedge Funds Are Hot Again</a>.=E2=80=9D For instance, =E2=80=9Cfamed inve=
stment firm Brevan Howard, which as recently as mid-2019 was struggling to =
stem an unprecedented client exodus, shut its flagship fund to investors ea=
rlier this year=E2=80=9D because investors were clamoring to give it more m=
oney than it could handle. =E2=80=9CHmm,=E2=80=9D you might think. If Breva=
n Howard (1) has more investor demand than it knows what to do with, and (2=
) just two years ago =E2=80=9Cwas struggling to stem an unprecedented clien=
t exodus,=E2=80=9D then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0perhaps it should reflect on the rec=
ent bad times, and use the current good times to=C2=A0<em>stem the client e=
xodus in advance?=C2=A0</em>Like, when the investors who took their money o=
ut two years ago are begging to put more money in now, conceptually, what y=
ou want to do is say =E2=80=9Csure I=E2=80=99ll take your money now but in =
exchange you have to promise not to take it out in two years when I start l=
osing all your money again.=E2=80=9D And, again, there really are technique=
s for that.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brevan Howard has found some?</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At Brevan Howard, the firm is de=
termined to avoid a repeat of the boom-and-bust cycle. And a key part of th=
at is talking more to investors, who in the old days didn=E2=80=99t get muc=
h more than an occasional update and a phone call. Now, even with Brevan Ho=
ward firmly in the throes of a turnaround, it=E2=80=99s focused on holding =
onto client assets when markets inevitably turn again.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe issue is with the ability of the manager to stop i=
nvestors from getting disillusioned and retain their confidence during inev=
itable periods of not-so-great performance,=E2=80=9D Landy said in a virtua=
l interview from his home office. =E2=80=9CWhat we are doing very thoughtfu=
lly and deliberately is trying to be the best partners for our clients.=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For him and other senior money manag=
ers at the firm, that means grabbing a microphone: they all have to record =
podcasts outlining the thinking behind their investments.</p></blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look if it were me I=E2=80=99d be demanding mul=
ti-year lockups but podcasting could probably work too.</p><table class=3D"=
header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Everything is securities fraud</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everything, I like to say, is securiti=
es fraud: If a public company does a bad thing, or a bad thing happens to i=
t, and it becomes public and the stock goes down, investors will sue. =E2=
=80=9CYou didn=E2=80=99t tell us about the bad thing,=E2=80=9D they will sa=
y, =E2=80=9Cso we bought the stock thinking it was very valuable, but then =
when we learned of the bad thing the stock went down and we lost money due =
to your deception.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, technicall=
y, this is not always securities fraud. Companies don=E2=80=99t actually ha=
ve an obligation to disclose everything that happens as soon as it happens.=
 If a moderately bad thing happens, and the company doesn=E2=80=99t say any=
thing for a while, and then the news comes out, that is not <em>technically=
=C2=A0</em>securities fraud.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is a =
small technicality that doesn=E2=80=99t matter much, because companies will=
 generally have said something that the bad thing renders untrue, or untrue=
-ish, or somewhat misleading. For instance, the company will say =E2=80=9Cw=
e have a code of ethics and tell our executives to behave well.=E2=80=9D Th=
en if the executives behave poorly, someone will sue the company, saying =
=E2=80=9Cyou told us that you have a code of ethics, so we believed your ex=
ecutives behaved well, but you neglected to tell us that they actually beha=
ve poorly.=E2=80=9D (This is the Goldman Sachs Group Inc. case that <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24841104.252088/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjIvbW9uZXktc3R1=
ZmYtZXZlcnl0aGluZy1zdGlsbC1taWdodC1iZS1zZWN1cml0aWVzLWZyYXVk/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB09fd9552" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">went to the Supreme Court</a>.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Or=C2=A0the company will have risk factors in its=C2=A0public filings, sa=
ying things like =E2=80=9Cif we get hacked that would be bad=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9Cif our chief executive officer is a sexual harasser that would be =
bad=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cif we violate the law that would be bad=E2=80=9D o=
r whatever. And then if it turns out the company had=C2=A0been hacked, or t=
he CEO is a harasser, or the company did violate the law, then investors co=
uld object: =E2=80=9CYou lied to us! You used words like =E2=80=98if we get=
 hacked,=E2=80=99 which implied that you had not been hacked, but in fact y=
ou had been hacked already! Your use of the word =E2=80=98if=E2=80=99 was f=
raud.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s really the la=
w I guess; here is a U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24841104.252088/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
c2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0xNTQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB16=
b99f02" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">en=
forcement action</a> from last week:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today announced that Pearson p=
lc, a London-based public company that provides educational publishing and =
other services to schools and universities, agreed to pay $1 million to set=
tle charges that it misled investors about a 2018 cyber intrusion involving=
 the theft of millions of student records, including dates of births and em=
ail addresses, and had inadequate disclosure controls and procedures.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC's order finds that Pearson made misleadi=
ng statements and omissions about the 2018 data breach involving the theft =
of student data and administrator log-in credentials of 13,000 school, dist=
rict and university customer accounts. In its semi-annual report, filed in =
July 2019, Pearson referred to a data privacy incident as a hypothetical ri=
sk, when, in fact, the 2018 cyber intrusion had already occurred. And in a =
July 2019 media statement, Pearson stated that the breach may include dates=
 of births and email addresses, when, in fact, it knew that such records we=
re stolen, and that Pearson had "strict protections" in place, when, in fac=
t, it failed to patch the critical vulnerability for six months after it wa=
s notified. The media statement also omitted that millions of rows of stude=
nt data and usernames and hashed passwords were stolen. The order also find=
s that Pearson's disclosure controls and procedures were not designed to en=
sure that those responsible for making disclosure determinations were infor=
med of certain information about the circumstances surrounding the breach.<=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24841104.252088/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjEvMzMtMTA5NjMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB265a=
d445" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the =
SEC=E2=80=99s order</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Jul=
y 25, 2019, Pearson=E2=80=99s management met to discuss the incident and ag=
ain decided that it was not necessary to issue a public statement regarding=
 it. On July 26, 2019, Pearson furnished on Form 6-K its report of interim =
results for the six months from January 1, 2019 through to June 30, 2019. I=
n the =E2=80=9CPrincipal risks and uncertainties=E2=80=9D section of that r=
eport, Pearson stated that a =E2=80=9C[r]isk of a data privacy incident or =
other failure to comply with data privacy regulations and standards and/or =
a weakness in information security, including a failure to prevent=C2=A0or =
detect a malicious attack on our systems, could result in a major data priv=
acy or confidentiality breach causing damage to the customer experience and=
 our reputational damage, a breach of regulations and financial loss.=E2=80=
=9D This statement, which remained unchanged from prior Forms 6-K, implied =
that no =E2=80=9Cmajor data privacy or confidentiality breach=E2=80=9D had =
occurred when Pearson knew months earlier about the AIMSweb 1.0 breach. Pea=
rson failed to consider how certain information about that breach should ha=
ve informed this risk disclosure.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Let=E2=80=99s assume=C2=A0that Pearson=E2=80=99s management was right a=
nd that =E2=80=9Cit was not necessary to issue a public statement regarding=
 it.=E2=80=9D (The SEC seems skeptical, but does not quite come out and say=
 that Pearson was obligated to disclose it immediately.) It could have just=
 burbled along keeping the breach quiet, until its next interim financial r=
eport was due. Then, if it just left in the usual risk factor =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cif we get hacked it=E2=80=99d be bad=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
at would become securities fraud; the hypothetical phrasing would imply tha=
t a hack had not happened, but in fact it had. I suppose Pearson could have=
 just=C2=A0<em>taken out=C2=A0</em>the risk factor, but that seems like muc=
h worse disclosure. (Certainly their risk of being hacked hadn=E2=80=99t go=
ne <em>down?</em>) The advanced move would be to tinker with it a bit: =E2=
=80=9Cif we get hacked it would be bad, and when we say that we don=E2=80=
=99t mean to imply that we have not been hacked, perhaps we have been hacke=
d, we=E2=80=99re not telling you.=E2=80=9D (For instance: =E2=80=9CRisk of =
a data privacy incident or other failure to comply with data privacy regula=
tions and standards and/or a weakness in information security, including a =
failure to prevent or detect a malicious attack on our systems, <strong><em=
>which may have already happened</em></strong>, could result in a major dat=
a privacy or confidentiality breach causing damage to the customer experien=
ce and our reputational damage, a breach of regulations and financial loss.=
=E2=80=9D) Even that might be too hypothetical for the SEC though. Really t=
he only move is to come clean. Your existing disclosure boxes you in.</p><t=
able class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpad=
ding=3D"0">
