rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a post from Joachim Klem=
ent</a> about vacation, pointing to a recent paper by Sima Jannati and Sara=
h Khalaf about stock analysts=E2=80=99 time off. The paper is called =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24841104.252088=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTM4Mj=
g1MjI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7beb9f1f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">A Ruffled Mind Makes a Restless Forecast: =
The Effect of Rest on Analyst Forecast Accuracy</a>,=E2=80=9D and here is t=
he abstract:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This paper tests w=
hether increased rest during holidays improves judgment tasks. We find that=
 earnings forecasts that are issued after holidays are, on average, 55 basi=
s points more accurate than those issued before holidays. This impact is co=
mparable to other determinants of analyst accuracy and is robust to alterna=
tive measures and explanations. Supporting the rest channel, we find that e=
nhancement in sleep time and sleep quality lead to more accurate forecasts.=
 Overall, we contribute to the literature by linking rest to financial deci=
sion-making.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Klement comments:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Making forecasts about company=
 earnings is a complex task that requires the analyst to weigh many differe=
nt factors. A stressed or exhausted analyst has reduced mental bandwidth an=
d is likely to engage in oversimplified reasoning and flawed forecasts. Mea=
nwhile, a well-rested analyst is able to weigh different factors more caref=
ully and should thus make better forecasts. And indeed, forecasts made by a=
nalysts in the first three workdays after a public holiday are more accurat=
e than forecasts made in the three days or the thirty days before the publi=
c holiday.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose the impli=
cation here is that yesterday=E2=80=99s, today=E2=80=99s and tomorrow=E2=80=
=99s editions of=C2=A0Money Stuff=C2=A0are as wise and thoughtful as you=E2=
=80=99re gonna get. The August news cycle is perhaps a confounding factor h=
owever.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=
=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The Poly Network hacker seems fun</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few weeks ago a hacker stole about $=
600 million of cryptocurrency from a decentralized finance protocol called =
Poly Network. Then Poly asked the hacker to give the money back, and the ha=
cker was like, sure, fine, I=E2=80=99ll give the money back. The money star=
ted coming back to a Poly wallet. =E2=80=9CCrypto Hackers Are Nice Now,=E2=
=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24841104.25=
2088/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMT=
EvY3J5cHRvLWhhY2tlcnMtYXJlLW5pY2Utbm93/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCa53491ce" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> was my hea=
dline</a>. =E2=80=9CThere is some chance this will turn out to be a hilario=
usly heartwarming story,=E2=80=9D I wrote.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
This weekend Kevin Dugan checked in on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/24841104.252088/aHR0cHM6Ly9ueW1hZy5jb20vaW50ZWxsaWdlbm=
Nlci8yMDIxLzA4L3RoZS1pbnNhbmUtb25nb2luZy1zYWdhLW9mLWEtdXNkNjAwLW1pbGxpb24tY=
3J5cHRvLXRoZWZ0Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB69e70449" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">how that=E2=80=99s going</a=
>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since then, the hacker parke=
d the equivalent of $240 million in a cryptowallet that=E2=80=99s purported=
ly shared with the Poly Network =E2=80=94 and then refused to give it the a=
ccess keys for a week. Mr. White Hat then raised the bar for when he will r=
eturn the funds, making himself the sole decider of when people will be abl=
e to get their own money back. On Wednesday, another $100 million or so was=
 returned =E2=80=94 the timing, and the trigger for the rest of the money, =
remains unknown. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe Pol=
y Network team is still negotiating with the hacker. And the primary goal i=
s to get one key back from the hacker,=E2=80=9D said Xuxian Jiang, the CEO =
of blockchain security firm Peckshield, which is working with Poly Network.=
 =E2=80=9CAt this stage, we really don=E2=80=99t want to make the hacker an=
gry to do something to jeopardize the funds.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah. (=E2=80=9CMr. White Hat=E2=80=9D is the nicknam=
e that Poly Network gave the hacker.) Well, maybe not heartwarming, but cer=
tainly still hilarious:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In his =
missives, he waxes philosophical about the nature of life, dropping referen=
ces to Martin Heidegger. =E2=80=9CI have been exploring the meaning of life=
 for a while. I hope my life can be composed of unique adventures, so I lik=
e [to] learn &amp; hack everything in order to fight against the fate. Sein=
 zum tode,=E2=80=9D he said, using a Heideggerian term for a state of being=
 that=E2=80=99s oriented toward one=E2=80=99s own death.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Despite the <em>nomme de paix</em>, this hacker is ambivalent=
 about the idea that what he=E2=80=99s doing fits into any neat ethical cat=
egory. In his communications, encrypted in publicly viewable ethereum trans=
actions, he refers to the heist he orchestrated as a =E2=80=9Cgame=E2=80=9D=
 nine times =E2=80=94 one where the losers get what they deserve.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s hard to prove that your loss i=
s my fault, especially when you are already gambling beyond your capability=
,=E2=80=9D he wrote in an all-caps message. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf you are still confused, ask some richer friends, wha=
t is money for?=E2=80=9D he wrote.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Sure returning the money=C2=A0<em>seems=C2=A0</em>kind, but=C2=
=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>it kind? What sort of lesson will the Poly users learn =
if the hacker steals their money and then gives it right back to them? He i=
s not here to just do some hacking, have a laugh, and give the money back; =
he is here to teach the Poly users some hard but necessary lessons about mo=
ney, about losses, about themselves, about the nature of being and time and=
 this harsh universe. =E2=80=9CSein zum Tode,=E2=80=9D he tells them, in al=
l-caps messages embedded in Ethereum blockchain transactions. Modern philos=
ophy is great.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cells=
pacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
